        <p>Sound waves being waves in general can be uniquely described via sinusoidals by having a frequency \(f= {1 \over T}\) where \(T\) is the time till one completed oscillation. Frequency is measured in units of Hertz(Hz) and can also be defined as \(f = {v \over \lambda}\) where \(v\) is the velocity of the wave and \(\lambda\) is the length. One popular application of using frequency is to define the sound wave as \(A\sin(\omega t)\) where \(A\) is pressure which can be measured in decibels (db), omega \(\omega=2\pi f\)\([{rad\over sec}]\) is the angular frequency and \(t\) is time\([s]\).
